<section>
  <h3>Building Your Skills</h3>
  <p>To be a successful web developer and to provide the greatest value to our important work, we have to build proficiency with a number of core skills including:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/frontier/home" title="Frontier Home">Frontier Development Stack</a></li>
    <li><a href="/h5c3/home" title="H5C3 Home">HTML5/CSS3</a></li>
    <li><a href="/javascript/home" title="Javascript Home">JavaScript</a></li>
    <li><a href="/qa/home" title="QA Home">Testing and Performance</a></li>
  </ul>
  <p>There is no order implied for learning these skills. They are mostly independent and can be worked on concurrently or sequentially.  One might want to start with the Frontier stack and build out a basic web app that can then be used to demonstrate other project work.</p>

  <h4>Learning Time</h4>
  <p>We have permission to allow you to spend up to 10% of your work time on training.  For every 8 hour day that you work, you can spend up to 45 minutes in learning activities.  It might be helpful to save that time up and use it in larger blocks.  You will need to plan your learning into your schedule in such a way as to minimize its impact on your story work.</p>
  <p>You might want to envision your project before you get started.  It can guide the examples you choose to demonstrate skills.  It's best if the parts integrate well into a single cohesive project.  It will be a better representation of you and your work.</p>

  <h4>FamilySearch Web Developer Ninja</h4>
  <p>After a developer has earned all four journeyman badges for the four core skills, they become <b>FamilySearch Web Developer Ninja</b> certified.  This honor means that they have qualified at a professional level, capable of producing high quality, well tested, and performant code.  It also indicates that they understand and have experience with our Frontier Web Stack.</p>
